      { id: "nvc-overview-what-it-is", name: "What it is", secs: 22, core: true, say: "Welcome. Today we explore Nonviolent Communication, often shortened to N V C. It is a way of speaking and listening developed by the clinical psychologist Marshall Rosenberg, and it is taught around the world by the Center for Nonviolent Communication. At its heart, it is simple. It is a practice for staying connected to ourselves and to other people, even when things feel hard." },
      { id: "nvc-overview-purpose", name: "The real purpose", secs: 21, core: true, say: "It helps to be clear about the purpose. Nonviolent Communication is not about winning an argument, and it is not about being nice or polite on the surface. Its aim is connection and mutual understanding, so that everyone's needs can be heard and considered. The goal is not to get our way. The goal is to understand and to be understood." },
      { id: "nvc-overview-four-parts", name: "The four parts", secs: 23, core: true, say: "Nonviolent Communication offers four parts to pay attention to. Observations, what actually happened, without judgement. Feelings, what we feel about it. Needs, the deeper human needs underneath those feelings. And requests, a clear, doable ask. Together these are sometimes called O F N R. Think of them less as a formula and more as four things worth noticing." },
      { id: "nvc-overview-example", name: "A small example", secs: 22, core: false, say: "Here is how the four parts might sound together. Instead of, you never listen to me, we might say: when I shared my idea and the room went quiet, I felt discouraged, because I really value being heard. Would you be willing to tell me what you took from it? Notice the difference. One is a verdict. The other is an honest invitation to connect." },
      { id: "nvc-overview-not-a-script", name: "Not a script, not manipulation", secs: 24, core: true, say: "This brings us to an important caveat. Nonviolent Communication is a mindset and a practice, not a rigid script to recite. If the four parts come out sounding robotic, the connection is usually lost. The words matter far less than the intention behind them. And to be clear, this is not a technique for managing or manipulating other people. It cannot change or control anyone, and it promises no particular outcome. It is one influential, widely taught approach, not the only one, and not settled scientific fact. We hold it gently." },
      { id: "nvc-overview-why-it-can-help", name: "Why naming helps", secs: 20, core: false, say: "There is some independent support for one piece of this. Research on what psychologists call affect labeling, including a well known study from U C L A, suggests that simply putting our feelings into words can calm the brain's alarm response. So the practice of naming a feeling, like I feel anxious, may genuinely steady us, quite apart from any conversation." },
      { id: "nvc-overview-safety-takeaway", name: "Safety and takeaway", secs: 23, core: true, say: "One firm boundary before we close. This lesson teaches a communication framework. It is not therapy or crisis support, and it does not replace professional mental health care. Nonviolent Communication is also not the right tool for situations involving abuse, coercion, or danger. There, your safety comes first. In the United States you can call or text nine eight eight for the Suicide and Crisis Lifeline, or call one eight hundred, seven nine nine, seven two three three for the National Domestic Violence Hotline. The takeaway is gentle. Nonviolent Communication is an invitation to connect with more honesty and care, practiced slowly, with patience for yourself." }
