  "nvc-needs": {
    id: "nvc-needs", title: "Universal human needs", topic: "needs",
    blurb: "Learn the Nonviolent Communication idea that beneath every feeling lives a universal human need, and that most conflict is a clash of strategies, not of needs.",
    takeaways: [ "Beneath every feeling lives a universal human need we all share.", "A need names no person; a strategy is one specific way to meet it.", "Most conflict is a clash of strategies, not of needs.", "One need has many roads — connection can be a call, meal, or walk." ],
    yearLabel: "2015",
    sources: [
      { org: "Center for Nonviolent Communication (CNVC)", title: "Feelings and Needs Inventory", url: "https://www.cnvc.org/store/feelings-and-needs-inventory", year: "" },
      { org: "PuddleDancer Press", title: "Nonviolent Communication: A Language of Life, 3rd Edition — Marshall B. Rosenberg", url: "https://nonviolentcommunication.com/product/nvc/", year: "2015" },
      { org: "Psychological Science (Lieberman, Eisenberger, Crockett, Tom, Pfeifer, Way)", title: "Putting Feelings Into Words: Affect Labeling Disrupts Amygdala Activity in Response to Affective Stimuli", url: "https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1111/j.1467-9280.2007.01916.x", year: "2007" },
      { org: "Wikipedia", title: "Manfred Max-Neef's Fundamental Human Needs", url: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manfred_Max-Neef's_Fundamental_human_needs", year: "" }
    ],
    segments: [
      { id: "nvc-needs-intro", name: "What we all share", secs: 20, core: true, say: "This is a lesson in Nonviolent Communication, or N V C, an approach developed by Marshall Rosenberg and the Center for Nonviolent Communication. It is one influential, widely taught way of understanding people, not the only one and not a proven scientific fact. At its heart is a hopeful idea: underneath everything we do are the same handful of human needs, and they are shared by every person alive." },
      { id: "nvc-needs-the-needs", name: "A few universal needs", secs: 22, core: true, say: "Rosenberg suggested that needs are universal. Things like connection and belonging. Safety and security. Autonomy, the freedom to choose. Rest and ease. Understanding, to be seen and heard. Meaning and purpose. Play and creativity. You can feel how these are not unusual or selfish. They are simply human. Whatever your culture or your story, you likely recognize every one of them in yourself." },
      { id: "nvc-needs-vs-strategies", name: "Needs versus strategies", secs: 23, core: true, say: "Here is the key distinction in this framework. A need is universal and names no particular person, action, or thing. A strategy is the specific way we try to meet it. So, I want you to text me back tonight, is a strategy. The need underneath might be reassurance, or connection. Rosenberg pointed out a useful clue: the moment your wish names a who, a what, a when, or a where, you have likely landed on a strategy, not the need itself." },
      { id: "nvc-needs-feelings-pointers", name: "Feelings as pointers", secs: 21, core: false, say: "In this view, feelings are not problems to fix. They are signposts. Pleasant feelings tend to point to needs that are being met. Painful feelings tend to point to needs going unmet. Loneliness can point toward connection. Frustration can point toward effectiveness or progress. So instead of, why do I feel so off, you might gently ask, what need of mine is asking for attention right now?" },
      { id: "nvc-needs-affect-labeling", name: "Why naming helps", secs: 22, core: false, say: "Naming the feeling and the need is worth doing for its own sake. Independent psychology research on what scientists call affect labeling supports this. In a two thousand seven study in the journal Psychological Science, Lieberman and colleagues found that simply putting feelings into words was linked to calmer activity in the amygdala, a region tied to emotional reactivity. Naming is not magic, and results vary, but quietly putting words to your inner state often takes some of the heat out of it." },
      { id: "nvc-needs-conflict", name: "Conflict is about strategies", secs: 23, core: true, say: "This reframes conflict in a powerful way. So often a clash is not a clash of needs at all, but of strategies. One partner wants a quiet evening in. The other wants a night out. The needs underneath, rest and connection, are not actually enemies. When two people drop down from their fixed strategies to the needs beneath them, new options often appear that neither had seen. This does not control or change the other person. It simply widens the conversation." },
      { id: "nvc-needs-many-strategies", name: "Many roads to one need", secs: 20, core: false, say: "There is real freedom here. A single need can be met by many different strategies. If the need is connection, a phone call works, and so does a shared meal, a letter, or a long walk. When we cling to one strategy as the only acceptable one, we suffer. When we hold the need warmly and stay curious about the path, we give ourselves and others room to breathe. The need is the destination. The strategy is just one road." },
      { id: "nvc-needs-safety-takeaway", name: "A boundary, and the heart of it", secs: 23, core: true, say: "To close, hold this honestly. This lesson teaches a communication framework. It is educational, not therapy or crisis support, and it is no substitute for professional mental health care. N V C is also not a tool for abuse, coercion, or danger. In those situations your safety comes first, and reaching for help is the strong choice. In the United States you can call or text nine eight eight for the Suicide and Crisis Lifeline, or call one eight hundred, seven nine nine, seven two three three for the National Domestic Violence Hotline. The gentle takeaway: behind every feeling is a need we all share, and behind most conflict is a clash of strategies, not of needs." }
    ],
  },
